/td><td style="border-bottom-color:#ffffff; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#ffffff; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#ffffff; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#ffffff; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:1.4pt; padding-right:1.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:206.65pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#ffffff; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#ffffff; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#ffffff; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#ffffff; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:1.4pt; padding-right:1.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:48.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#ffffff; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#ffffff; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#ffffff; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#ffffff; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:1.4pt; padding-right:1.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:206.65pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#ffffff; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#ffffff; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#ffffff; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#ffffff; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:1.4pt; padding-right:1.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:31.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#ffffff; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#ffffff; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#ffffff; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#ffffff; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:1.4pt; padding-right:1.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:206.65pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 0pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:center"><a name="heading"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Written evidence from the Law Commission (SLC0060)</span></p><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">ntroduction</span></h1><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Law </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Commission and Scottish Law Commission recently completed a review of the legal framework governing level crossings. We published a report on 25 September 2013, together with a draft Bill and draft health and safety Regulations. We also published an analys</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is of consultation responses and an economic impact assessment.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Here we set out the background to this project, our major findings and a summary of our proposals. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The full report and supporting documents may be found at: </span><a href="http://lawcommission.justice.gov.uk/publications/level-crossings.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://lawcommission.justice.gov.uk/publications/level-crossings.htm</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Law Commissions’ work is most relevant to the Transport Select Committee’s question: h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ow should the legislation governing level crossings be updated? </span></p><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">background</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase"> </span></h1><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We were asked by the Department for Transport and the Office of Rail Regulation to take on this project as part of our 10th Programme of law reform in 2008. The ORR had carried ou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t a consultation in which stakeholders, including Network Rail and highways authorities, had strongly supported a review of the legislation on level crossings because the law is outdated, unclear, difficult to access and to understand. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A consultation pape</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r was published in July 2010 and we consulted for four months, including meetings with a wide range of stakeholders and site visits to a variety of mainline and heritage railways and tramways. Policy continued to develop as a result of consultation. Both s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ets of Commissioners then approved the policy we had developed and gave permission to instruct Parliamentary counsel. Counsel drafted a Bill and Regulations under the Health and Safety at Work etc Act 1974. A final report was approved by both Commissions i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n the summer of 2013 and the report, draft Bill, draft Regulations, analysis of consultation responses and impact assessment were published in September 2013. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This project took longer than we expected for several reasons. The scale of the project was huge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and wide-ranging, as is apparent from the size of the report. It involved intricate consideration of highway law and railway law, as well as land law, planning law, compulsory purchase, health and safety, criminal law and regulatory theory. The law in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sco</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is fundamentally different from that in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in some places, for example in relation to rights of way. The project required close collaboration between the two Law Commissions. Each step of the project was peer-reviewed by both Commissio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ns within different timetables. We also co-operated closely with a wide range of stakeholders. The end result was a 300-page report, containing over 100 recommendations. </span></p><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">Scope</span></h1><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The terms of reference of the project were:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 56.7pt 12pt 85.05pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“To review the law relating to leve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l crossings, and make recommendations, with a view to providing a modern regulatory framework for level crossings and to simplify and modernise that law.”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The aims of the project were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:1pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 47.96pt; padding-left:12.54pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To provide a modern regulatory framework for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">level crossings</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:1pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 47.96pt; padding-left:12.54pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To si</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mplify the law and make it more accessible</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:1pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 47.96pt; padding-left:12.54pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To modernise the law</span></li></ul></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-29.49pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no reference in the terms of reference to safety. While a good regulatory system will facilitate safety improvements, we do not claim that our recommendations will directly, of them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">selves, improve safety.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">recommendations</span></h1><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our findings and recommendations fall into three broad areas: safety and convenience; closure of level crossings and rights of way. Most of our recommendations are given effect in the draft Level Crossings Bill and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">draft Level Crossings Plans Regulations. In addition, there are some areas which we investigated, but did not make significant recommendations for law reform. These are considered in the final Part of the report and include: criminal offences; signs; plann</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing law; barrow crossings and open crossings; and finally, the design of level crossings.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We summarise our recommendations briefly here:  </span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Safety and Convenience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (Report Part 2)</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Findings</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We found that the legislation governing level crossings is complex </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and antiquated including</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 70.56pt; padding-left:7.94pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">thousands of private special Acts dating back to the early nineteenth century, which authorised the building of each individual railway</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 70.56pt; padding-left:7.94pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">public general Acts relating to the railway; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 70.56pt; padding-left:7.94pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">general health and safety legislation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 70.56pt; padding-left:7.94pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e Level Crossings Act 1983. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is not always easy to know which law is still in force and which takes precedence. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition, we found that the current procedures for changing protective arrangements at level crossings under level crossing orders is cum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bersome and tends to lead to arrangements (barriers, lights and so on) remaining in place even when they are no longer the most suitable solution. This can compromise the convenience and efficiency of both the road and rail networks and inconvenience has a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> close relationship to safety. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We found that effective management of level crossings, and the efficiency of road and rail at the crossing, can be significantly affected by good (or poor) co-operation between the railway operator and the highway authority </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or private beneficiary of the crossing. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We also found that the convenience of the railway tends to take precedence as railway operators are under no obligation to consider the convenience of non-rail users when deciding what arrangements are put in place.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.17</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We considered the enforcing authorities and found that there is a lack of clarity as to when ORR is responsible for enforcement following road-rail incursions. This goes beyond level crossings and applies to railways more generally. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.18</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oncluded that the regulation of level crossings could be simplified by removing other sources of regulation and leaving level crossings to be governed by the Health and Safety at Work etc Act 1974, which already applies to the railways and to workplaces in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> general. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.19</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We considered whether decisions should be restricted to the Secretary of State, as health and safety are reserved matters, but concluded that it was more appropriate for decisions about individual level crossings to be made at a more local level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, balancing the local powers in respect of highways and roads with national oversight of safety. So we recommended that the decisions described below should be made by the Secretary of State in relation to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, Scottish Ministers in relation to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scotlan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and Welsh Ministers in relation to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.20</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We prop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ose four levels of regulation, with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ORR </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as the enforcement authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">General duties under Part 1, HSWA 1974 including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">duty on employer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and self-employed person</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to ensure, so far as reasonably practicable, that persons not in their employment are not exposed to risks to their health or safety.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This includes duties volunteers on most railways, but we have also recommended the extension of these duties to heritage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">railways which are not employers. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Regulations made under HSWA 1974 (such as regulations empowering the Sec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">retary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of State to require a highway authority to take action near a level crossing, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">plac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a sign or paint</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> road markings).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Level crossi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng plans.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Initially we didn’t think that any replacement was needed for level crossing orders, as the railway operators and other duty-holders are responsible for assessing risk and putting suitable arrangements in place which reduce risk so far as reasona</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bly practicable. However, it was clear from consultation responses that those in the industry find it helpful to have a record of what has been decided. Level Crossing plans are agr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eed sets of arrangements for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a particular crossing. They are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">optional, but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">once agreed, enforc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eable. We have drafted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">health and safety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Regulations for making such plans, under HSWA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 1974</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A level crossing plan may be made in respect of any crossing, whether public or private, unlike level crossing orders which are only for highway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s or roads to which the public has access. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Lastly, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ecretary of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, Scottish or Welsh Ministers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have the power to issue a direction for the purposes of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">safety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> convenience at a crossing. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is intended for use as a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> last resort or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">exceptional</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> circumstances.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.21</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Nothing in these recommendations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the requirements on the railway operators to inspect level crossings, carry out risk assessments on a regular basis and put suitable arrangements in place </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in order to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">keep risk as low as reasonably p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">racticable. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.22</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In order to facilitate the effective management of level crossings, we also recommend: </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tatutory duty to co-operate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;  and </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a statutory duty to consider the convenience of all users.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.23</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These duties will be imposed upon railway operators and hi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ghway/traffic authorities. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.24</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We also recommend that the delineation of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enforcement responsibilities of ORR and HSE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should be clarified. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.25</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We recommend that certain outdated or obsolete statutory provisions relating to level crossing safety should be disapplied. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.26</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Closure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Report Part 3)</span></p><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Findings</span></h3><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.27</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Level crossings are difficult to close under the current law.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.28</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A level crossing always poses a ri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sk to safety and can be inconvenient to both road and rail as well. Network Rail and ORR are committed to closing level crossings where possible, but this must be balanced against the needs of communities in maintaining access across the railway. </span></p><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Recommen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">dations</span></h3><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.29</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We recommend a new, more streamlined system for deciding whether it is in the public interest to close a level crossing with or without a replacement. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.30</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The decision would be made by the Secretary of State, Scottish or Welsh Ministers who would be r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">equired to consider all relevant issues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and decide whether the scheme as a whole was in the public interest. That would include:  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the safety of the public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the convenience of the public</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the efficiency of the transport network (including the network of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">public paths)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the cost of maintaining the crossing</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(5)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the need for the crossing and its significance for the local community (including the protection of heritage)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(6)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the costs and environmental impact of any works needed to replace the crossing or upgrade other</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> crossings. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.31</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We recommend a combined consent procedure, which provides for: the closure of the level crossing; the extinguishment of the rights of way across the railway; compensation; the diversion of any right of way; planning permission or other permiss</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ions required to build any replacement bridge or underpass; compulsory purchase powers and compensation for compulsory purchase. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.32</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A closure decision would be subject to challenge to the High Court by way of statutory judicial review. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.33</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition, we have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recommended health and safety regulations to enable highway authorities to be required to place signs, or paint lines or take other necessary action on the highway near a level crossing. </span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Rights of way</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (Report parts 4 and 5)</span></h2><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Findings</span></h3><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.34</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Lastly, there are area</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s of land law and the law of rights of way which are not entirely clear in relation to level crossings. Some level crossings were created by the grant of an easement (or servitude in Scotland) across the railway, others were created by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">model clauses from t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Railway Clauses Consolidation Act 1845</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a special Act, and this has led to some confusion over how far the law of easements applies to these crossings. </span></p><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></h3><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.35</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recommend the clarification of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">certain issues, including: </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It should not be possible to create a private right of way across the railway by prescription (long user). </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It should not be possible to create a public right of way across the railway (dedicate a highway) impliedly. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Statutory rights of way should be trea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ted in the same way as easements if the owner agrees to sell the right of way (and therefore close the level crossing permanently) to the railway operator. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 96.4pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.89pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, some additional proposals have been made, including amendment to the Land Reform (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">land</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) Act 2003 to make it clear that access rights are not exercisable across the railway, but to empower Scottish Ministers to create new level crossings or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">subject private level crossings to access rights for the purposes of that Act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 28.35pt 3pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">Cost:benefit anal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">ysis</span></h1><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.36</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We provided a total net present value of between £717 million and £1,464 million, with £1,402 being the best estimate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">over a 60 year period</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This period r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eflect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the life of the capital investment element of level crossing equipment. We have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">worked c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">losely with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">key stakeholders, Network Rail and ORR in particular, to inform our view of the likely cost/benefit impact of our proposals. We have taken a conservative approach and have used figures that we considered likely to under-estimate benefits and ov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er-estimate costs. Both the costs and benefits of a new safety regime are relatively modest when compared with the resource implications of a new closure procedure. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.37</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The costs of the new safety regime are expected to be negligible and largely of an advisor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y and administrative nature commensurate with a co-operative relationship. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">most significant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">benefit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> comes from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">savings from reduced delays and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">waiting times at level crossings following closure.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We have also estimated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reduced risk of catastrophic acci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dents/near misses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The safety benefits </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">range from just under £1 million to about £36 million over 60 years. The low [£1 million] estimate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reflects the possibility of there b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eing no reduction in the probability of an incident as a result of our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recommended </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 56.7pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.61pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.38</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The costs of the new closure procedure are significant mainly as a result of construction costs of alternatives to level crossings, bridge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">underpass. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The costs and benefits of closure derive from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">AXIAT model, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">designed by RSSB, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which Network Rail will use </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in practice as a first hurdle before</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> carrying out a full business case analysis of public vehicular level crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This model takes into account all relevant costs and benefits and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">produces a net figure. The net benefit estima</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tes range from about £717 million to £1428 million over 60 years and includes operating and maintenance cost savings. Critically, achieving the maximum NPV value depends on access to sufficient funding in addition to law reform </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in order to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">facilitat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> crossing closure.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="line-height:11pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">              </span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:6pt 28.35pt 0pt 70.9pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt">Level Crossings (2013) Law Com No 339; Scot Law Com No 234. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 28.35pt 0pt 70.9pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt">Level Crossings (2013) Law Com No 339; Scot Law Com No 234, Part 6. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 28.35pt 0pt 70.9pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt">Existing powers are discussed in para 3.5 of the Report. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 28.35pt 0pt 70.9pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt">S 68. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 28.35pt 0pt 70.9pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt">This is not a complete list of the recommendations we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt"> make on rights of way. See Parts 4 and 5 of the report for further details. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 28.35pt 0pt 70.9pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt">For guidance on how waiting times and the costs of delays are calculated, see the Department for Transport’s Transport Analysis Guidance at </span><a href="http://www.dft.gov.uk/webtag/documents/expert/unit3.5.6.php"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.dft.gov.uk/webtag/documents/expert/unit3.5.6.php</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt"> . The figures used in the Law Commissions’ impact assessment were prepared for the report by Network Rail and the Rail Safety and Standards Board. </span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p></body></html>